english:
  title: Preface to the Collection of Poeun
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: "I have long reflected that when Confucius refined the Book of Songs down to three hundred poems, he did so because those verses spring from the mandate of Heaven and the bonds of humanity, flowing into statecraft and the customs of the people. From the ceremonial hymns of temples and courts above to the humble songs of marketplace and alley below—all that stirs the goodness within us and rebukes our idle desires is gathered there. Does poetry's worth then depend on quantity? Poetry transformed into the Elegies, the Elegies into lyric verse and rhapsodies, which transformed again into five-word and seven-word forms, until we reach regulated verse—the ultimate perfection of poetry's evolution. Yet the single phrase \"thoughts free from artifice\" encompasses all three hundred poems. Does the Way of poetry truly rest on abundance?\n\nThe Master Poeun, Lord Jeong, illumined the late era of the former dynasty with his learning of heaven and humanity and his talents in statecraft. Now his sons, Jongsseong and Jongbon, have brought me his remaining manuscripts and requested: \"Our father's poems and writings were nearly lost in the chaos of upheaval. Fortunately, these few hundred pieces survive. We wish to carve them into wood to pass them to posterity. You and our father knew each other well throughout life—would you grace the beginning of this collection with a word?\" \n\nMoved by their plea, I received the work and read it. The language surges with power, the spirit drifts free of worldly dust. Its harmony never descends into excess, its beauty never lapses into mere ornament. The aura of sincerity does not waver with fortune or misfortune, the resolve of righteousness does not falter with ease or hardship. Here we see the fruit of self-cultivation perfected, and what emerges in the music of his verse reflects this same truth. Thus \"thoughts free from artifice\" transcend the distinction between orthodox and variant forms of poetry.\n\nShould the Middle Kingdom one day gather the poems of tributary states, this collection will surely be transmitted alongside those of Masters Mokun and Taun, and let the scholars of China know that in the Eastern Land there flourishes a kingdom of letters. Is this not a glorious thing?\n\nAlas, the Master's conduct and the arc of his life are recorded in the national histories—I need not elaborate further."
  footnotes:
    - Poeun (포은) was the pen name of Jeong Mongju (정몽주, 1337-1392), a great Neo-Confucian scholar and statesman of Goryeo.
    - '"Thoughts free from artifice" (思無邪) is a famous phrase from the preface to the Book of Songs, expressing the essence of poetry''s moral purpose.'
    - Mokun (牧隱) and Taun (陶隱) refer to other celebrated Korean scholars whose collected works were likewise esteemed.
    - Ha Ryun (河崙, 1347-1416) was a prominent Neo-Confucian scholar who served both Goryeo and early Joseon.
